          setPerspective("G");
          setAxesVisible(0,0);
        </slate>
      </interactive>
    </figure>

  </paragraphs>
  <paragraphs>
    <title>Special Products</title>
    <p></p>
    <p>
      Now let's turn our attention to a special product called "the product of conjugates."  Conjugates are pairs of binomials whose only difference are the operators.  In one expression the operation is addition and in the other expression the operation is subtraction.  Generically, we refer to conjugates as <m>(a+b)</m> and <m>(a-b)</m>.  Let's see what happens when we multiply those two expressions.
      <md>
        <mrow>(a+b)(a-b)\amp=a^2-ab+ab-b^2</mrow>
        <mrow>\amp=a^2-b^2</mrow>
      </md>
      The remarkable thing that occurred is that the two linear terms in the expansion added to zero, leaving behind the binomial <m>a^2-b^2</m>.  The product of conjugates is the only product of binomials of form <m>(ax \pm h)(bx \pm k)</m> that expands and simplifies to another binomial.  In all other cases the expansion and simplification of <m>(ax \pm h)(bx \pm k)</m> results in a trinomial.
    </p>
    <p>
      Because the linear terms always add to zero when we multiply conjugates, we frequently jump directly from <m>(a+b)(a-b)</m> or <m>(a-b)(a+b)</m> to <m>a^2-b^2</m>.  Three examples are shown below.
      <me>(x-4)(x+4)=x^2-16</me>
      <me>(3x+7y)(3x-7y)=9x^2-49y^2</me>
      <me>(5+y^3)(5-y^3)=25-y^6</me>
      Let's shift our attention to one of the most common errors made in mathematics.  It involves the square of a binomial.  Consider the following. <me>(x+y)^2</me>  For some folks, it is very tempting to just distribute the exponent to <m>x</m> and <m>y</m>.  So tempting, in fact, that many actually do it!  The problem is that exponents do not distribute over addition.  Exponents distribute over multiplication and division.  The only operations that distribute over addition and subtraction are multiplication and division.  Let's see what the expansion and simplification of <m>(x+y)^2</m> looks like when executed correctly.
      <md>
        <mrow>(x+y)^2\amp=(\highlightb{x}+\highlight{y})(\highlightg{x}+\highlightr{y})</mrow>
        <mrow>\amp=\highlightb{x} \cdot \highlightg{x}+\highlightb{x} \cdot \highlightr{y}+\highlight{y} \cdot \highlightg{x}+\highlight{y} \cdot \highlightr{y}</mrow>
        <mrow>\amp=x^2+xy+xy+y^2</mrow>
        <mrow>\amp=x^2+2xy+y^2</mrow>
      </md>
      Ah!  If we just distribute the exponent to <m>x</m> and <m>y</m>, we miss the two products of <m>xy</m>.  OI-vey!
      For most folks the described error can be avoided by routinely making the first statement of the expansion process the writing out of two occurrences of the factor side by side.
    </p>

    <example>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Expand and simplify <m>(5x-4)^2</m>.
        </p>
      </statement>
      <solution>
        <p>
          <md>
            <mrow>(5x-4)^2\amp=(5x-4)(5x-4)</mrow>
            <mrow>\amp=25x^2-20x-20x+16</mrow>
            <mrow>\amp=25x^2-40x+16</mrow>
          </md>
        </p>
      </solution>
    </example>

  </paragraphs>
  <paragraphs>
    <title>Products of Polynomials with More than Two Terms</title>
    <p></p>
    <p>
      As you know, polynomials are not limited to two terms.  For example, consider the following product.
      <me>(x+3)(x^2+7x+2)</me>
      We can begin the expansion process by distributing <m>(x^2+7x+2)</m> to both terms of the binomial <m>(x+3)</m>.
      <md>
        <mrow>(\highlightg{x}+\highlightr{3})\highlight{(x^2+7x+2)}\amp=\highlightg{x} \cdot \highlight{(x^2+7x+2)}
              +\highlightr{3} \cdot \highlight{(x^2+7x+2)}</mrow>
        <mrow>\amp=\highlightg{x} \cdot \highlight{x^2}+\highlightg{x} \cdot \highlight{7x}+\highlightg{x} \cdot \highlight{2}+\highlightr{3} \cdot \highlight{x^2}+\highlightr{3} \cdot \highlight{7x}+\highlightr{3} \cdot \highlight{2}</mrow>
        <mrow>\amp=x^3+7x^2+2x+3x^2+21x+6</mrow>
        <mrow>\amp=x^3+10x^2+23x+6</mrow>
      </md>
      Once again, we should turn our focus to one specific equivalence in the last expansion.
      <me>(\highlightg{x}+\highlightr{3})\highlight{(x^2+7x+2)}=\highlightg{x} \cdot \highlight{x^2}+\highlightg{x} \cdot \highlight{7x}+\highlightg{x} \cdot \highlight{2}+\highlightr{3} \cdot \highlight{x^2}+\highlightr{3} \cdot \highlight{7x}+\highlightr{3} \cdot \highlight{2}</me>
      What we what to focus is the fact that every term of the binomial <m>x+3</m> was multiplied with every term of the trinomial <m>x^2+7x+2</m>.
    </p>

    <example>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Apply the last observation to the expansion of <m>(3y-1)(y^2+4y-8)</m>.
        </p>
      </statement>
      <solution>
        <p>
          <md>
            <mrow>(\highlightg{3y}\highlightr{-1})\highlight{(y^2+4y-8)}\amp=\highlightg{3y} \cdot \highlight{y^2}+\highlightg{3y} \cdot \highlight{4y}+\highlightg{3y} \cdot \highlight{-8}-\highlightr{1} \cdot \highlight{y^2}-\highlightr{1} \cdot \highlight{4y}-\highlightr{1} \cdot \highlight{-8}</mrow>
            <mrow>\amp=3y^3+12y^2-24y-y^2-4y+8</mrow>
            <mrow>\amp=3y^3+11y^2-28y+8</mrow>
          </md>
        </p>
      </solution>
    </example>

    <p>
        When employing the strategy of multiplying all terms of the polynomial on the left with all terms of the polynomial on the right, we need to be very deliberate in our process.  I always distribute the fist term in the left polynomial to each term of the right polynomial, then the second term of the left polynomial to each term of the right polynomial, etc.
    </p>  

    <example>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Expand and simplify <m>(x^2-9x+4)(2x^2+x-4)</m>.
        </p>
      </statement>
      <solution>
        <p>
          <md>
            <mrow>\amp(\highlightg{x^2}\highlightr{-9x}+\highlightb{4})\highlight{(2x^2+x-4)}</mrow>
            <mrow>\amp \phantom{={}} \phantom{={}}=\highlightg{x^2} \cdot \highlight{2x^2}+\highlightg{x^2} \cdot \highlight{x}+\highlightg{x^2} \cdot \highlight{-4}-\highlightr{9x} \cdot \highlight{2x^2}-\highlightr{9x} \cdot \highlight{x}-\highlightr{9x} \cdot \highlight{-4}</mrow>
            <mrow>\amp \phantom{={}} \phantom{={}} \phantom{={}} \phantom{={}} \phantom{={}} \phantom{={}} \phantom{={}} \phantom{={}} \phantom{={}} \phantom{={}} \phantom{={}} \phantom{={}} \phantom{={}} \phantom{={}} \phantom{={}} \phantom{={}} \phantom{={}} \phantom{={}} \phantom{={}}+\highlightb{4} \cdot \highlight{2x^2}+\highlightb{4} \cdot \highlight{x}+\highlightb{4} \cdot \highlight{-4}</mrow>
            <mrow>\amp \phantom{={}} \phantom{={}}=2x^4+x^3-4x^2-18x^3-9x^2+36x+8x^2+4x-16</mrow>
            <mrow>\amp \phantom{={}} \phantom{={}}=2x^4-17x^3-5x^2+40x-16</mrow>
          </md>
        </p>
      </solution>
    </example>

  </paragraphs>

    <exercises>

      <exercisegroup>
        <introduction>
          <p>
            Expand and simplify each product.
          </p>
        </introduction>

          <exercise>
            <statement>
              <p>
                <m>(x+3)(x-14)</m>
              </p>
            </statement>
            <solution>
              <p>
                <m>
                  \begin{aligned}[t]
                  (x+3)(x-14)\amp=x^2-14x+3x-42\\
                  \amp=x^2-11x-42
                  \end{aligned}
                </m>
              </p>
            </solution>
          </exercise>

          <exercise>
            <statement>
              <p>
                <m>(3y+1)(2y-4)</m>
              </p>
            </statement>
            <solution>
              <p>
                <m>
                  \begin{aligned}[t]
                  (3y+1)(2y-4)\amp=6y^2-12y+2y-4\\
                  \amp=6y^2-10y-4
                  \end{aligned}
                </m>
              </p>
            </solution>
          </exercise>

          <exercise>
            <statement>
              <p>
                <m>(9x-2)(x^2+4x-1)</m>
              </p>
            </statement>
            <solution>
              <p>
                <m>
                  \begin{aligned}[t]
                  (9x-2)(x^2+4x-1)\amp=9x^3+36x^2-9x-2x^2-8x+2\\
                  \amp=9x^3+34x^2-17x+2
                  \end{aligned}
                </m>
              </p>
            </solution>
          </exercise>

          <exercise>
            <statement>
              <p>
                <m>-3x^2(4x^2-6x+5)</m>
              </p>
            </statement>
            <solution>
              <p>
                <m>
                  -3x^2(4x^2-6x+5)=-12x^4+18x^3-15x^2
                </m>
              </p>
            </solution>
          </exercise>

          <exercise>
            <statement>
              <p>
                <m>(4x+5y)(4x-5y)</m>
              </p>
            </statement>
            <solution>
              <p>
                <m>
                  \begin{aligned}[t]
                  (4x+5y)(4x-5y)\amp=16x^2-20xy+20xy-25y^2\\
                  \amp=16x^2-25y^2
                  \end{aligned}
                </m>
              </p>
            </solution>
          </exercise>

          <exercise>
            <statement>
              <p>
                <m>(3x+5)^2</m>
              </p>
            </statement>
            <solution>
              <p>
                <m>
                  \begin{aligned}[t]
                  (3x+5)^2\amp=(3x+5)(3x+5)\\
                  \amp=9x^2+15x+15x+25\\
                  \amp=9x^2+30x+25
                  \end{aligned}
                </m>
              </p>
            </solution>
          </exercise>

          <exercise>
            <statement>
              <p>
                <m>(x+3)(x-7)(x-2)</m>
              </p>
            </statement>
            <solution>
              <p>
                <m>
                  \begin{aligned}[t]
                  (x+3)(x-7)(x-2)\amp=(x^2-7x+3x-21)(x-2)\\
                  \amp=(x^2-4x-21)(x-2)\\
                  \amp=x^3-2x^2-4x^2+8x-21x+42\\
                  \amp=x^3-6x^2-13x+42
                  \end{aligned}
                </m>
              </p>
            </solution>
          </exercise>

          <exercise>
            <statement>
              <p>
                <m>(x^4+8y^2)(-3x^4+5y^2)</m>
              </p>
            </statement>
            <solution>
              <p>
                <m>
                  \begin{aligned}[t]
                  (x^4+8y^2)(-3x^4+5y^2)\amp=-3x^8+5x^4y^2-24x^4y^2+40y^4\\
                  \amp=-3x^8-19x^4y^2+40y^4
                  \end{aligned}
                </m>
              </p>
            </solution>
          </exercise>

          <exercise>
            <statement>
              <p>
                <m>(3-7w^7)^2</m>
              </p>
            </statement>
            <solution>
              <p>
                <m>
                  \begin{aligned}[t]
                  (3-7w^7)^2\amp=(3-7w^7)(3-7w^7)\\
                  \amp=9-21w^{7}-21w^{7}+49w^{14}\\
                  \amp=9-42w^7+49w^{14}
                  \end{aligned}
                </m>
              </p>
            </solution>
          </exercise>

          <exercise>
            <statement>
              <p>
                <m>(x+4)^3</m>
              </p>
            </statement>
            <solution>
              <p>
                <m>
                  \begin{aligned}[t]
                  (x+4)^3\amp=(x+4)(x+4)(x+4)\\
                  \amp=(x^2+4x+4x+16)(x+4)\\
                  \amp=(x^2+8x+16)(x+4)\\
                  \amp=x^3+4x^2+8x^2+32x+16x+64\\
                  \amp=x^3+12x^2+48x+64
                  \end{aligned}
                </m>
              </p>
            </solution>
          </exercise>

          <exercise>
            <statement>
              <p>
                <m>(3x^2-4)(x^2-x+6)</m>
              </p>
            </statement>
            <solution>
              <p>
                <m>
                  \begin{aligned}[t]
                  (3x^2-4)(x^2-x+6)\amp=3x^4-3x^3+18x^2-4x^2+4x-24\\
                  \amp=3x^4-3x^3+14x^2+4x-24
                  \end{aligned}
                </m>
              </p>
            </solution>
          </exercise>

          <exercise>
            <statement>
              <p>
                <m>-x(-x^3-4x^2+2x+3)</m>
              </p>
            </statement>
            <solution>
              <p>
                <m>
                  -x(-x^3-4x^2+2x+3)=x^4+4x^3-2x^2-3x
                </m>
              </p>
            </solution>
          </exercise>

          <exercise>
            <statement>
              <p>
                <m>(5y+2)^2</m>
              </p>
            </statement>
            <solution>
              <p>
                <m>
                  \begin{aligned}[t]
                  (5y+2)^2\amp=(5y+2)(5y+2)\\
                  \amp=25y^2+10y+10y+4\\
                  \amp=25y^2+20y+4
                  \end{aligned}
                </m>
              </p>
            </solution>
          </exercise>

        </exercisegroup>

      </exercises>

    </section>
